- You’re hitting an ABI mismatch. Emulators for “Pixel Pro” typically run `x86_64`, but your native build only packages `armeabi-v7a` and `arm64-v8a`. The warning is usually like: “Unsupported ABI: x86_64. Device supports: [x86_64,…]; app supports: [armeabi-v7a, arm64-v8a].”

### What to do
- If you’re deploying to an emulator:
 - Add `x86_64` to `ndk.abiFilters` in `app/build.gradle.kts` (or remove the `abiFilters` block to build all ABIs).
 - Alternatively, use an ARM emulator image so `arm64-v8a` works.
- If you’re deploying to a physical Pixel Pro:
 - It’s `arm64-v8a`, which you already include. If it still fails, ensure the native library actually builds for `arm64-v8a` (clean/rebuild), and that no stray `jniLibs` folder overrides packaging.

### Why you saw the warning
- Gradle/ADB warns when the target device/emulator’s CPU architecture doesn’t match any packaged native library in your APK.

Status: Based on your `app/build.gradle.kts`, you currently package `armeabi-v7a` and `arm64-v8a` only. Add `x86_64` (for emulator) or remove `abiFilters` to resolve the architecture mismatch.

### Summary
- Root cause: emulator is `x86_64`; APK has only `armeabi-v7a`/`arm64-v8a`.
- Fix: include `x86_64` in `ndk.abiFilters` in `app/build.gradle.kts` or remove the filters; or run an ARM emulator image."}]},{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"<user_query>
